==Fiction==

===Novels===
* {{cite book |last=Canon |first=Jack |title=The Normandy Code: Nick Carter Killmaster #202 |date=1985 |publisher=Diamond |isbn=978-0441586127}} Nick Carter must retrieve a plaster Madonna containing the computer codes of all the Pershing missiles.
* {{cite book |last=Evans |first=Linda |author-link=Linda Evans (author) |title=Sleipnir |date=1994 |publisher=Baen |isbn=0-671-87594-9 |url=http://www.baenebooks.com/p-388-sleipnir.aspx}} The first few chapters are based on the real-life experiences of a Pershing missile guard with the [[2nd Battalion, 4th Infantry Regiment]].
* {{cite book |last=Hagberg |first=David |author-link=David Hagberg |title=Countdown |date=1990 |publisher=Tor |isbn=978-0812509649 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0xfWf6fKuasC}} The codes for Pershing missiles based at Ramstein Air Base are stolen.
* {{cite book |last=Montgomery |first=R. A. |author-link=R. A. Montgomery |title=Trio: Rebels in the New World: Almost Lost |date=1990 |publisher=Starfire |isbn=978-0553284621}} In post-apocalyptic America of 2015, a would be dictator uses seven National Guard Pershing 1 missiles painted red to attack Denver.
* {{cite book |last=Mudrick |first=Victor |title=In the Wrong Hands |publisher=Xlibris |date=2002 |isbn=978-1462818969 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=G6ilj2vn_qQC}} A Pershing missile escaped destruction during the [[Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces Treaty]] elimination and terrorists use it to threaten London.{{Self-published inline|certain=yes|date=December 2017}}
* {{cite book |last=Niven |first=Larry |author-link=Larry Niven |last2=Pournelle |first2=Jerry |author-link2=Jerry Pournelle |title=[[Footfall]] |date=1985 |publisher=Del Rey |isbn=978-0345323446}} During an alien invasion, Pershing missiles are retargeted to attack an orbiting ship.

===Film===
* {{cite AV media |last=Bernds |first=Edward (director) |title=[[The Three Stooges in Orbit]] |date=1962}} There are two short scenes with a Pershing 1 at 1:17:06 and 1:18:51.
* {{cite AV media |last=Hughes |first=John (director, writer) |author-link=John Hughes (filmmaker) |title=[[Weird Science (film)|Weird Science]] |date=1985 |time=56:50}} A Pershing II missile is created from 31 January 1983 cover of ''Time''.
* {{cite AV media |last=Scott |first=Tony (director) |author-link=Tony Scott |title=[[Crimson Tide (film)|Crimson Tide]] |date=1995 |time=4:19}} Cmdr. Hunter is watching the news when the newscaster states "Threatened to use nuclear arms on the United States and Japan... should anyone, including the Russian Army, attempt to move in on him." The missile being erected is a Pershing II.
* {{cite AV media |last=Anderson |first=Wes (director) |author-link=Wes Anderson |title=[[Rushmore (film)|Rushmore]] |date=1998 |time=1:33}} The character is wearing the inverted insignia of the [[56th Field Artillery Command]].
* {{cite AV media |last=Levy |first=Shawn (director) |author-link=Shawn Levy |title=[[Night at the Museum: Battle of the Smithsonian]] |date=2009 |time=1:02}} The scene at the [[National Air and Space Museum]] includes prop versions of the Pershing II and SS-20 missiles.

===Television===
* {{cite episode |last=Moder |first=Dick (director) |title=The Murderous Missile |series=[[Wonder Woman (TV series)|Wonder Woman]] |date=21 April 1978}} Wonder Woman must stop the hijacking of an experimental thought controlled missile. The missile prop is a Pershing, probably the [[Estes Industries|Estes]] model.
* {{cite episode |last=Roh |first=Mike (director) |title=Liftoff |series=[[Eureka! (TV series)|Eureka!]] |date=2011 |time=12:28}} The interceptor missile launch is U.S. Army footage of a Pershing 1a missile launch.
* {{cite episode |series=[[Deutschland 83]] |date=2015}} The series is set in 1983 West Germany during the Pershing II deployment. Series opening includes a Pershing 1a being erected.

