* {{cite AV media |last=Pritchett |first=C. B. |title=German Air Force Pershing 1b launch |publisher=Martin Marietta |url=https://fb8ba84a-a-62cb3a1a-s-sites.googlegroups.com/site/pershingmissilesources/artwork/MMA-%20Pershing%201b%2001_%2011x8.5.jpg?attachauth=ANoY7cpDltZIkvhY15vOTZxaaofi0xnbJuUrgbzPlOfe_Hg6utSHxTaWtNPrgxAlFTY9Bz9DbxKcVbx-ludKqoGv7ovxtk7Ffy_c4gD3ET4QJ5NXuk9TWd_tYraW3_dUK74-reA69McHPHOk3pAAGyGI99qqj83bw6xD6F7YTY0hIWqbPFys0NjqEXfQglYbIDClCmIWk7Ifc6BiG7cc-u5bMWSfV7bXp9zlBYI2yqYfzWlvPlIbmSN7xkyEjLppSJz6JzsaAOwy&attredirects=0}}
* {{cite AV media |last=Pritchett |first=C. B. |title=U.S Army Pershing II |publisher=Martin Marietta |url=https://fb8ba84a-a-62cb3a1a-s-sites.googlegroups.com/site/pershingmissilesources/artwork/MMA-%20Pershing%20II%2001_11x8.5.jpg?attachauth=ANoY7coJTu3P6GJYRYqVz8FLLbwFNHf1ayxJ6-0-47qNBwvpITU0pdcYTrqVR5k_RRiEyYTcCF3x0S_F0DvbpqzLwIfYmZB03fR4u8m1Hsb_UOsOFaAIGHemI7Fom798WVDy5FxG8z9HCBN-TIekCqDHdwN8Dyo6qIQcDDr0LrN7Z7cHwN3stavhVGsbxScAUKsyp7fx-3ogr7K-LSQ0ca6dlvm7ZL0OvY3e2S2AJoDDu7JGzlGUML_pAdZ5tScrfwuoMsZR9dLt&attredirects=0}}
* {{cite AV media |last=Finley |first=George |title=The Final Countdown |date=1988 |url=http://www.militaryart.com/uploads/The_Last_Countdown_-_Pershing_II.jpg}}
** {{cite AV media |title=The Blackjack Pershing Chapter of the United States Artillery Association Presents the Commemorative Painting Pershing II— The Final Countdown by George Finley |date=1988 |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/249796318 |format=PDF |type=Booklet}}
** George Finley is a military artist who was the commander of the [[74th U.S. Army Field Artillery Detachment]], supporting [[Missile Wing 1]] of the German Air Force. In 1988, the Blackjack Pershing Chapter of the United States Field Artillery Association commissioned a painting to commemorate the decommissioning of the Pershing system. 501 signed prints of ''The Final Countdown'' were created. The print is now available for sale again through his website.
* {{cite AV media |last=Tsereteli |first=Zurab |author-link=Zurab Tsereteli |title=Good Defeats Evil |date=1990 |url=https://fb8ba84a-a-62cb3a1a-s-sites.googlegroups.com/site/pershingmissilesources/artwork/Good%20Defeats%20Evil%20658.jpg?attachauth=ANoY7crK7KB03hpX-TH9L1pwYMfLBZ77R89wFynRGS6pk2cmHTsorgWZ8uIlmFlZtLLvZo0im-31obVSZPD97Vp2n48J38Lqj0V3ZvGXEgCeV0UHgWSI2XuuK7q1J4U-1OSAJupAkegnTiTMjvNcLAZnim-AJXgrG67sAr4RSwDf4NMOLxBq9YBZLQYklMsNJkBuVirSZu1rQ6ye6D8vSQT1jQvo_lJprXwOAkXh5gbY9WhNTihT8xjroDgCGhL7nDZ8OgCS4sIN&attredirects=0}}
**Tsereteli created a sculpture using sections of scrapped US Pershing and Soviet SS-20 nuclear missiles. The sculpture, entitled Good Defeats Evil is a 39 foot high, 40 ton monumental bronze statue of St George fighting the dragon of nuclear war. It was donated to the UN by the Soviet Union in 1990 and placed on the grounds of the UN headquarters in New York City. A series of works based on the sculpture that also incorporated scrap from the missiles were released in a limited series of 160 each.
** {{cite book |title=Good Defeats Evil |type=Brochure |date=1990 |publisher=Universal Art Corporation |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/250934631 |format=PDF}}
** [http://www.coldwar.org/thumbnails/tsereteli/goodevilstatuesmall.jpg A 39-inch-tall sculpture]
** [http://www.coldwar.org/thumbnails/tsereteli/gve.gif An enamel plaque with a copper back]
** [https://scontent-iad3-1.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-xap1/t31.0-8/s960x960/10636435_10152525916551334_5618931307552300196_o.jpg Bronze medallion]
** The INF Treaty Missile Commemorative uses missile shards with a 7½ bronze medallion

==Memorabilia==
===World Memorial Fund for Disaster Relief===
[[Leonard Cheshire]] created the World Memorial Fund for Disaster Relief in 1990. The charity obtained Pershing and SS-20 scrap material and created memorabilia for fund raising.

* {{cite AV media |title=World Memorial Fund for Disaster Relief badge |date=1991 |url=https://scontent-iad3-1.xx.fbcdn.net/hphotos-xpa1/l/t31.0-8/p526x395/10835261_10152525930966334_8568900936848117260_o.jpg}} The badge is the group logo, a World War I whistle.
* {{cite AV media |title=World Memorial Pens |publisher=[[Parker Pen Company]] |date=1991}}
**Parker created the World Memorial Pens, a series of pens and mechanical pencils with a Memorial Fund badge on the crown or clip, with half the proceeds going to the fund.
** [http://www.penbox.co.uk/images/ref.1093.world.memorial.jpg Duofold Black International Fountain Pen]
** Duofold Black International Ball Pen
** Duofold Black International Fountain Pen and Ball Pen; 90192
** Sonnet Fountain Pen
** Laque Black Ball Pen; 81632
** Laque Black Ball Pen and Mechanical Pencil
** Stainless GT Ball Pen; 81732
** Stainless GT Ball Pen and Mechanical Pencil
** 14K Dimonite G Ball Pen; 81532
** [https://web.archive.org/web/20141127050237/http://finestedition.com/zencart/images/Parker/418039.jpg 14K Dimonite G Ball Pen and Mechanical Pencil]
* {{cite AV media |title=Five Presidents Pen |publisher=Parker |date=1991 |url=http://parkerpens.net/bilder_pennor/limitededition/five_presidents-1200.jpg}}
** On 4 November 1991 the [[Ronald Reagan Presidential Library]] opened in Simi Valley, California. The then five living presidents, [[Richard Nixon]], [[Gerald Ford]], [[George H. W. Bush]], [[Jimmy Carter]] and [[Ronald Reagan]] were present at the opening. Parker presented each with a black ballpoint Duofold Centennial with the Presidential Seal on the crown formed from scrap material and the barrel engraved with signatures of the presidents. The pen was also offered in a walnut box with the names of all five presidents and the Presidential Seal.

==Other==
