'''Samuel Abt''' (born 1934) is an American sports [[journalist]] and [[author]] who covered professional cycling for 31 years,<ref>{{cite web|last=Startt|first=James|title=Pro Cycling Interview: Samuel Abt|url=http://www.bicycling.com/news/pro-cycling/samuel-abt|publisher=Bicycling.com|accessdate=December 19, 2012|date=February 2012|quote=The veteran journalist speaks exclusively with Bicycling about covering 31 Tours de France, the changes he's seen in the sport, and bicycle racing's rich narrative lines.}}</ref>  publishing articles in the [[New York Times]] and [[International Herald Tribune]], among others. He devoted much time to chronicling the careers of English-speaking riders, especially [[Lance Armstrong]] and [[Greg LeMond]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Abt|first=Samuel|title=Rip Lance Time|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/27/opinion/rip-lance-time.html?pagewanted=all|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=December 19, 2012|date=August 26, 2012|quote="I hear that you've written a book about Greg LeMond," Armstrong told me when we first met in 1992. "You going to write one about me?" We had known each other about five minutes. "Yes, I will," I replied, "if you ever amount to much." The book appeared in 2000.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Abt|first=Sam|title=LeMond Glances Backward From the Top of Alpe d'Huez|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/07/19/sports/19iht-lemond.2.t.html|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=December 19, 2012|date=July 19, 1999|quote=LeMond always did like to have a good time, to enjoy the food and wine along the way to winning the Tour de France three times, in 1986, '89 and '90. He might have won a few more but — in a similarity to Lance Armstrong's diagnosis of cancer in 1996 — lost more than a season after he was shot and nearly killed in a hunting accident in 1987.}}</ref>

Abt wrote 10 books on professional cycling, including ''In High Gear: The World of Professional Bicycle Racing'', ''Lemond: The Incredible Comeback of an American Hero'', and the acclaimed ''Breakaway: On the Road with the Tour de France''. According to VeloPress, "He is the only American to have been awarded the medal of the Tour de France for distinguished service to the race."<ref>{{cite web|title=Samuel Abt|url=http://velopress.com/authors/samuel-abt/|work=VeloPress Authors|publisher=VeloPress|accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref>

Abt is retired and lives in a suburb of Paris.

